BEGIN_PGML
Using the digits 2 through [$n], find the number of different [$a]-digit numbers such that: 
a.  Digits cannot be repeated and must be written in increasing order. For example, 234678 is okay, but 324678 is not.

    [_____]{$ans1}


a.  Digits _can_ be repeated and must be written in _non-decreasing_ order. For example, 24448 is okay, but 24484 is not.

    [_____]{$ans2}   



END_PGML

####################
# Solution
####################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a.  There are  [`{[$m] \choose [$a]}`] numbers. We simply choose [$a] of the [$m] digits and once chosen put them in increasing order.


a.  This requires stars and bars. Use a star to represent each of the [$a] digits in the number, and use their position relative to the bars to say what numeral fills that spot. So we will have [$a] stars and [$j] bars, giving [`{[$p] \choose [$j]}`] numbers.   



END_PGML_SOLUTION

